qas.question: Where did some of the US Air Force traditions come from?
What traditions does the US Air Force have?
What organization did the US Air Force adopt "Challenge Coins" from?
What does the roof stomp tradition signify in the US Air Force?

answers.text: welcome a new commander or to commemorate another event, such as a retirement

context: Many of the U.S. Air Force's formal and informal traditions are an amalgamation of those taken from the <a0_0>Royal Air Force<a0_0/> (e.g., dining-ins/mess nights) or the experiences of its predecessor organizations such as the U.S. Army Air Service, U.S. Army Air Corps and the U.S. Army Air Forces. Some of these traditions range from <a1_0>"Friday Name Tags" in flying units<a1_0/> to an annual "Mustache Month." The use of "challenge coins" is a recent innovation that was adopted from the <a2_0>U.S. Army<a2_0/> while another cultural tradition unique to the Air Force is the "roof stomp", practiced by Air Force members to <a3_0>welcome a new commander or to commemorate another event, such as a retirement<a3_0/>.
